1. How to create your own package in Java?

A package in Java is a namespace used to organize related classes and interfaces.
We can create our own package using the package keyword at the top of a Java program.
For example: package com.mycompany.util;. After compiling the program using javac -d . 
ClassName.java, the package folder structure will be created automatically. 
Packages help in avoiding class name conflicts and improve code reusability and maintainability.

2. What is a Marker Interface?

A marker interface is an empty interface that does not contain any methods. 
It is used to mark a class so that the JVM or compiler can provide special behavior for that class. 
When a class implements a marker interface, it indicates that the class has some special capability. 
A common example is Serializable, which tells Java that an object can be converted into a byte stream. 
Marker interfaces are mainly used for runtime checks.

3. What is Serialization and Deserialization?

Serialization is the process of converting a Java object into a byte stream so that it can be stored in a file or transferred over a network. 
Deserialization is the reverse process, where the byte stream is converted back into the original Java object. 
This mechanism is commonly used in file storage, caching, and network communication. 
To perform serialization, a class must implement the Serializable interface.

4. What is the transient keyword?

The transient keyword in Java is used to indicate that a variable should not be serialized. 
When an object is serialized, transient variables are ignored and not saved in the byte stream. 
This is useful for storing sensitive data like passwords or temporary data that should not be persisted. 
When the object is deserialized, transient variables are assigned default values such as 0 for numbers or null for objects.

5. Difference between Interface and Abstract Class (Real-Time Example)

An interface in Java is used to define a contract that classes must follow. 
It contains method declarations that implementing classes must define. 
A class can implement multiple interfaces, which supports multiple inheritance.

An abstract class is a class that cannot be instantiated and may contain both abstract methods and concrete methods (methods with implementation).
A class can extend only one abstract class because Java does not support multiple inheritance with classes.

Real-time example:
Consider a Vehicle system. 
An interface like Vehicle can declare methods such as start() and stop(), and classes like Car, Bike, and Bus implement these methods in their own way.
An abstract class like Car can provide common functionality such as fuelType() or speed() while leaving some methods abstract for subclasses to implement.